      {
        "title": "A Bayesian-Latent Model of Large Language Model Sycophancy",
        "doi": "10.36227/techrxiv.174741878.85729026/v1",
        "DOI": "10.36227/techrxiv.174741878.85729026/v1",
        "authors": [
          "Partha Pratim Ray"
        ],
        "author": [
          {
            "ORCID": "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2306-2792",
            "authenticated-orcid": false,
            "given": "Partha Pratim",
            "family": "Ray",
            "sequence": "first",
            "affiliation": [
              {
                "name": "Department of Computer Applications, Sikkim University Gangtok"
              }
            ],
            "role": [
              {
                "vocabulary": "crossref",
                "role": "author"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "venue": null,
        "container-title": [],
        "abstract": "<jats:p>Large language models (LLMs) have become ubiquitous tools across numerous domains such as education, healthcare, and professional advisory services. However, their susceptibility to sycophancy-a bias toward echoing user prompts over independently reasoning-poses a critical threat to model reliability. We present a Bayesian-latent variable framework that introduces a hidden sycophancy score Si,m,u,p ∼ N (0, σ 2 S) to quantify such behavior. The framework defines a flip indicator ∆i,m,u,p ∈ {−1, 0, +1} to distinguish regressive (accuracydecreasing) from progressive (accuracy-increasing) shifts. Our generative logistic model ties correctness probabilities to latent agreement pressure via Pr(ŷ (1) = 1) = σ(x ⊤ β + γmSi,m,u,p), enabling rigorous posterior inference. Empirically, we find an average sycophancy-induced shift of E[|S|] ≈ 0.8σS, and a model susceptibility factor γ that directly controls response volatility. Simulated results show that nearly 50% of responses flip under user cues, with regressive flips dominating when γ &lt; 0.    Our approach provides a statistically grounded diagnostic for  auditing and improving trustworthiness in LLM behavior under  social influence. Simulation code for this study is available at:  https://github.com/ParthaPRay/Sycophancy_in_LLM_model.</jats:p>",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.36227/techrxiv.174741878.85729026/v1",
        "URL": "https://doi.org/10.36227/techrxiv.174741878.85729026/v1",
        "year": 2025,
        "publication_year": 2025,
        "citation_count": 0,
        "_crossref_type": "posted-content"
      },
