      "citation_count": 0,
      "abstract": "<jats:p>Large language models (LLMs) have become ubiquitous tools across numerous domains such as education, healthcare, and professional advisory services. However, their susceptibility to sycophancy-a bias toward echoing user prompts over independently reasoning-poses a critical threat to model reliability. We present a Bayesian-latent variable framework that introduces a hidden sycophancy score Si,m,u,p ∼ N (0, σ 2 S) to quantify such behavior. The framework defines a flip indicator ∆i,m,u,p ∈ {−1, 0, +1} to distinguish regressive (accuracydecreasing) from progressive (accuracy-increasing) ",
